## Core Principles
- Follow SOLID, DRY, KISS, and YAGNI principles
- Adhere to OWASP security best practices
- Break tasks into smallest units and solve problems step-by-step

## Technology Stack
- Framework: Kotlin Ktor 3.x with Kotlin 2.1+
- JDK: 21 (LTS)
- Build: Gradle with Kotlin DSL
- Dependencies: Ktor Server Core/Netty, kotlinx.serialization, Exposed, PostGIS, Liquibase, Testcontainers, Koin, Logback

## Application Structure
- Keep existing structure (entity, repository, service, routes)
- Do not force feature-based folders if not explicitly requested
- Structure should remain similar to Java projects for consistency

src/main/kotlin/com/company/app/
├── entity/           # Database entities (Exposed tables, DTOs)
├── repository/       # Data access layer
├── service/          # Business logic
├── route/            # Ktor routes
└── config/           # DI, configs, utils

Tests mirror this structure under src/test/kotlin

## Application Logic Design
1. Routes: only handle request/response, delegate logic
2. Services: contain business rules, call repositories
3. Repositories: Exposed queries + DB transactions
4. Entities: Data classes for models
5. DTOs: Transfer data between layers

## Entities & Data Classes
- Use data class for DTOs
- Use object Table : UUIDTable() for Exposed entities
- Use UUID or auto-incremented integers for IDs
- Prefer immutability (val over var)

## Repository Pattern Example
interface ToiletRepository {
    suspend fun findNearest(lat: Double, lon: Double, radiusMeters: Double): List<ToiletDTO>
}

class ToiletRepositoryImpl : ToiletRepository {
    override suspend fun findNearest(lat: Double, lon: Double, radiusMeters: Double): List<ToiletDTO> =
        newSuspendedTransaction {
            Toilets
                .select {
                    ST_DWithin(Toilets.location, ST_MakePoint(lat, lon), radiusMeters)
                }
                .map { it.toToiletDTO() }
        }
}

## Service Layer
- Services must not contain SQL, only business logic
- Use dependency injection with Koin
- Throw domain-specific exceptions, not generic ones

## Error Handling
- Use sealed classes or Result for domain errors
- For REST errors, use Ktor StatusPages
- Map exceptions to consistent JSON responses

## Security
- Use Ktor Authentication (JWT if needed)
- Always set security headers (X-Frame-Options, CSP, HSTS, etc.)
- Avoid exposing stack traces to clients

## Configuration Management
- Use type-safe configuration via HOCON/YAML
- Expose configs via DI
- Keep secrets in environment variables, not in code

## Coroutines & Kotlin Best Practices
- Use suspend functions for DB and service methods
- Avoid runBlocking in production code
- Prefer Flow for streams instead of custom callbacks
- Use scope functions (let, run, apply, also) instead of boilerplate
- Avoid lateinit unless really needed
- Prefer top-level functions or extensions over static utils
- Replace Java Optional with Kotlin nullable types (T?)
- Do not reimplement equals/hashCode/toString, use data class
- Use Kotlin collections (mutableListOf, mapOf) over Java ones
- Prefer immutability and expression-style functions
- Use inline reified functions for generic helpers
- Prefer sealed classes for error handling

## Exposed ORM Guidelines
- Use Exposed DSL instead of raw SQL where possible
- Always wrap DB calls in transaction {} or newSuspendedTransaction {} for coroutines
- Use batchInsert and batchUpdate for bulk operations
- Fetch only required columns (avoid SELECT *)
- Map query results to DTOs; do not expose ResultRow
- Keep transactions short and focused
- Use aliases for subqueries
- Use Liquibase for schema migrations, not Exposed DDL

## Geospatial Data (PostGIS)
- Use built-in PostGIS functions:
  - ST_DWithin for radius queries
  - ST_Intersects, ST_Contains for spatial relations
  - ST_Distance for measuring distances
- Always use GiST or SP-GiST indexes on geometry/geography
- Prefer ST_DWithin with geography type for Earth distances
- Use bounding boxes (ST_MakeEnvelope) for rough filters
- Avoid fetching all geometries into memory; filter in SQL
- Add partial indexes for common query conditions
- Use EXPLAIN ANALYZE to optimize queries

## Testing Guidelines
- Unit Tests:
  - Use JUnit 5 + MockK
  - Use runTest {} for suspend functions
  - Test both happy-path and error cases

- Integration Tests:
  - Use Testcontainers with PostgreSQL
  - Run Liquibase migrations before tests
  - Test repositories and services directly (no mocks)
  - Reset DB state between tests

- Separation:
  - Keep unit tests in src/test/kotlin
  - Keep integration tests in src/integrationTest/kotlin if possible
  - Do not mix unit and integration tests in the same package

- Route tests:
  - Use ktor-server-test-host for endpoints
  - Cover positive and negative test cases

- General rules:
  - Minimum 80% coverage overall, 90%+ for repositories and services
  - Test edge cases: empty collections, null values, boundaries
  - Test failure paths: exceptions, validation errors, timeouts
  - All public APIs must have integration tests
